895,"month":10,"day":28,"city":"Colorado Springs","state":"Colorado","cause":"tuberculosis (long-term)"},"gender":"male","parents":{"father_name":"Dr. Horatio Adams","mother_name":"Ann Bethune Dunkin"},"marriages":[{"marriage_number":1,"spouse_id":"HD3341","children_ids":["HD3347","HD3348","HD3349"],"date_year":1868,"end_year":1895,"end_type":"death"}],"number_of_marriages":1,"has_descendants_documented":true,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":false,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"tags":["physician","harvard_graduate"],"notable":{"is_notable":true,"notable_category":["medicine","social_reform"],"notable_blurb":"Waltham physician; Colorado College trustee; civic leader","primary_url":"https://www.thecrimson.com/article/1895/11/2/obituary-dr-benjamin-faneuil-dunkin-adams/","primary_url_label":"Harvard Crimson obituary"},"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"career","header":"Harvard 1860, Harvard Medical highest honors 1864","body":"He graduated from Harvard in 1860 and immediately began studying medicine with Dr. Jeffries Wyman of Cambridge, soon entering Harvard Medical School. He took his MD in 1864 with the highest honors after surgical interneships at Rainsford Island state hospital and Massachusetts General Hospital, then studied in London and Paris."},{"number":2,"category":"death","header":"Tuberculosis forced retirement to Colorado at 43","body":"Overwork in Waltham broke his health in 1882 and he moved his family to Colorado Springs. Though he never resumed practice, he led an active civic life there until his death in 1895 — Colorado College trustee from 1887, friend and patron of the Colorado Springs Gazette editor Steele."},{"number":3,"category":"family","header":"Descended from Peter Faneuil and Israel Putnam","body":"He counted among his ancestors Peter Faneuil — who gave his name to Faneuil Hall — and Israel Putnam, the famous Revolutionary War general. His mother Ann Bethune Dunkin carried the South Carolina Dunkin line; the unusual middle name 'Faneuil Dunkin' was inherited."}],"cross_connections":[],"sources":[{"url":"https://www.thecrimson.com/article/1895/11/2/obituary-dr-benjamin-faneuil-dunkin-adams/","label":"Harvard Crimson obituary Nov 2, 1895"},{"label":"Colorado Springs Gazette tribute Oct 30, 1895"}],"former_ids":[],"education":[],"career":[],"military_service":[],"institutions":[{"institution_id":"INST002"}],"landmarks":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"artworks":[],"research_tags":[],"quotes":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"is_placeholder":false,"residence":{},"baptism":{},"slug":"benjamin-adams-1839"},"HD3347":{"id":"HD3347","has_descendants_documented":true,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":true,"generation_from_thomas":9,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":true,"descent_from_john_talcott":true,"is_thomas_descendant":true,"is_talcott_descendant":true,"is_easter_egg":false},"parents":{"father_id":"I00303","mother_id":"HD3341"},"gender":"male","bio":{"display_name":"Edward Brinley Adams","first_name":"Edward","middle_name":"Brinley","last_name":"Adams","married_names":[],"photo_url":"https://res.cloudinary.com/dc5clrqtw/image/upload/v1777485495/edwardadams_bv8tva.jpg"},"birth":{"year":1871,"month":5,"day":7,"city":"Waltham","state":"Massachusetts"},"death":{"year":1922,"month":3,"day":24,"city":"Cambridge","state":"Massachusetts","cause":"stroke"},"tags":["harvard_graduate","lawyer"],"sources":[{"url":"https://www.jstor.org/stable/1329010?seq=8","label":"Harvard Law Review memorial 1922"}],"notable":{"is_notable":true,"notable_category":["law","education"],"notable_blurb":"Harvard Law School Librarian 1913-1922","primary_url":"https://www.jstor.org/stable/1329010?seq=8","primary_url_label":"Harvard Law Review memorial"},"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"career","header":"Harvard Law School Librarian for nine years","body":"After serving as Librarian of the Social Law Library in Boston (1909-1913), he was appointed Librarian of the Harvard Law School on September 1, 1913. He served until his sudden death from stroke on March 24, 1922 — devoting himself to the school 'with complete devotion.'"},{"number":2,"category":"character","header":"1894 horseback wire-fence accident changed his life","body":"Spending his vacation in Colorado Springs in summer 1894, he galloped through the Country Club gate where a careless steward had stretched cattle wire across the entrance. His horse fell with him; he lay unconscious nearly a month and remained an invalid for close upon a year. His sensitive organization 'never regained its old power of rapid and forcible expression.'"},{"number":3,"category":"education","header":"Led his class at Harvard Law in scholarship","body":"In his first year at Harvard Law (1892-93) he led his class in scholarship and was recognized by his fellow students as a man of brilliant ability. He was an editor of the Harvard Law Review, a member of Pow-Wow Club and Phi Delta Phi."}],"marriages":[{"marriage_number":1,"spouse_id":"I00304","children_ids":["HD3350"],"date_year":1896,"end_type":"divorce"},{"marriage_number":2,"spouse_id":"I00305","children_ids":["HD3352","HD3353"],"date_year":1916,"location_city":"Boston","location_state":"Massachusetts","end_year":1922,"end_type":"death"}],"number_of_marriages":2,"cross_connections":[],"institutions":[{"institution_id":"INST002"}],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"military_service":[],"residence":{},"baptism":{},"burial":{"plot_notes":"Mount Feake Cemetery, Waltham MA"},"former_ids":[],"education":[],"career":[],"is_placeholder":false,"slug":"edward-adams-1871"},"HD3348":{"id":"HD3348","has_descendants_documented":false,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":true,"generation_from_thomas":9,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":true,"descent_from_john_talcott":t